<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6388&amp;p=68536#p68536</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6388&amp;p=68536#p68536"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Why do USB drives need to be &quot;ejected&quot;]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6388&amp;p=68536#p68536"><![CDATA[
The indicator light isn't sufficient. The same problem existed with disk drives in the past. You look at light. It's off. You start to eject it. OS happens to start writing at that moment. You lose data. This is why (almost?) all Macs had disk drives whose eject was controlled by the OS, and why most Macs have OS-controlled power as well. The OS can then avoid ejecting/powering off when the filesystem is in an inconsistent state, and avoid initiating any activity once the operation has begun.<br /><br />Too bad the Mac OS lacked process protection back then, so that it would crash fairly often, and thus cause data loss anyway. Funny how it wasn't a hardware issue, but a software one that they didn't address in the OS. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Tue Oct 12, 2010 2:45 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
